Question 1

The data contained in lake.csv, reports the data of 29 lakes in Florida and contains three variables:

  • NIN = Average influent nitrogen concentration.
  • TN = Mean annual total nitrogen concentration.
  • TW = Water retention time.

The outcome the research was interested in was TN. Calculate the correlation coefficient between NIN and TN.

Use of cor() and cor.test() is not permitted.

lake <- read_csv("../Data/lake.csv")

n <- nrow(lake)
z_x <- (lake$NIN - mean(lake$NIN)) / sd(lake$NIN)
z_y <- (lake$TN - mean(lake$TN)) / sd(lake$TN)

R <- sum(z_x * z_y) / (n - 1)
round(R, 4)
## [1] 0.0699



Question 2

Fit a least squares regression model using just NIN as the predictor. Report the formula for the model you create.

Use of lm() is not permitted.

# Slope
b1 <- R * (sd(lake$TN) / sd(lake$NIN))
round(b1, 4)
## [1] 0.0121
# Intercept
b0 <- mean(lake$TN) - b1 * mean(lake$NIN)
round(b0, 4)
## [1] 1.8685

Formula:

\(\hat{y} = 1.8685 + 0.0121 \cdot x\)



Question 3

Plot the previous questions model on a scatterplot of the data.

ggplot(lake, aes(x = NIN, y = TN)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_abline(intercept = b0, slope = b1) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))



Question 4

Using the model from question 2, create a scatter plot of the residuals.

# Predicted/Fitted Values
lake$y_hat <- b0 + b1 * lake$NIN

# Residuals
lake$resid <- lake$TN - lake$y_hat

# Residual Plot
ggplot(lake, aes(x = y_hat, y = resid)) +
  geom_point(
    shape = 21,
    stroke = 1,
    fill = "firebrick2",
    size = 3
  ) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = 3) +
  ylab("Residuals") + xlab("Fitted Values") +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

  • Note that the values from the NIN column could have also been plotted on the x-axis.



Question 5

Using the model from question 2, create a Q-Q plot of the residuals and answer the question are the residuals normally distributed?

# Q-Q Plot
ggplot(lake, aes(sample = resid)) +
  stat_qq(
    shape = 21,
    stroke = 1,
    fill = "firebrick2",
    size = 3
  ) +
  stat_qq_line() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

The residuals show a systematic departure from a straight line at the lower end and are best considered not normally distributed.



Question 6

Assume the data satisfies all the necessary assumptions. Assess whether the slope is significantly different from 0, reporting the test-statistic, p-value, and confidence interval. What do you conclude?

  • Use of lm() is not permitted.
# Squared standard error of the residuals
res_sq_se <- (sum(lake$resid^2) / (n - 2))

# Sum of squared deviations
ss_x <- sum((lake$NIN - mean(lake$NIN))^2)

# Slope standard error
s_b1 <- sqrt(res_sq_se / ss_x)

# Degrees of freedom
P <- 1
df <- n - P - 1

# Test H0: b1 = 0
t_stat <- (b1 - 0) / s_b1

p <- pt(t_stat, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# T_crit
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

# 95% CI on Slope
lower <- b1 - t_crit * s_b1
upper <- b1 + t_crit * s_b1
## T = 0.3639
## df = 27
## p = 0.7188
## 95% CI: [-0.0561, 0.0802]

We fail to reject the hypothesis that the slope is equal to 0.

Question 8

Remove the outliers flagged by the MAD-median rule, re-calculate your model, and state its formula.

You are allowed to use lm() for this and the remaining questions.

lake_cln <- lake |> 
  filter(out == FALSE) |> 
  select(NIN, TN, TW)

model_cln <- lm(TN ~ NIN, data = lake_cln)

# Intercept
round(model_cln$coefficients[1], 4)
## (Intercept) 
##      0.2867
# Slope
round(model_cln$coefficients[2], 4)
##   NIN 
## 0.562

Formula:

\(\hat{y} = 0.2867 + 0.562 \cdot x\)

Question 10

Create a scatter plot and a Q-Q plot of the residuals for the data that had outliers removed. Would you feel comfortable running a t-test to evaluate the slope of this data? Why or why not?

# Scatterplot
ggplot(lake_cln, aes(x = NIN, y = model_cln$residuals)) +
  geom_point(
    shape = 21,
    stroke = 1,
    fill = "firebrick2",
    size = 3
  ) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = 3) +
  ylab("Residuals") +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

# Q-Q Plot
ggplot(lake_cln, aes(sample = model_cln$residuals)) +
  stat_qq(
    shape = 21,
    stroke = 1,
    fill = "firebrick2",
    size = 3
  ) +
  stat_qq_line() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

There is no clear suggestion of heteroscedasticity in the residuals. However, the Q-Q plot shows departures from normality in the lower tail. I would not feel comfortable trusting the test and would probably look for robust alternatives.
